  "answer": "**Allama Iqbal's poems in *Bang-E-Dara* (divided into three parts in the corpus) occasionally reference or are dedicated to specific historical figures, primarily in their titles or opening lines. Here are the relevant ones:**\n\n- **\"Abdul Qadir Ke Naam\"** (Bang-E-Dara Part 2, Chapter 8): Dedicated to Abdul Qadir (likely a contemporary figure or scholar known to Iqbal).[^1]\n- **\"Swami Ram Tirath\"** (Bang-E-Dara Part 2, Chapter 23): Praises Swami Ram Tirath (1873–1906), the Indian poet and philosopher who embraced Vedantic mysticism.[^2]\n- **\"Ram\"** (Bang-E-Dara Part 3, Chapter 17): Celebrates Ram (Rama), portrayed as a spiritual exemplar and \"Lamp of Light\" for Hindustan, drawing from Indian tradition.[^3]\n- **\"Tazmeen bar sher-e Aneesi Shamlu\"** (Bang-E-Dara Part 3, Chapter 24): A poetic response to a couplet by Aneesi Shamlu (likely a poet), referencing Pir Sanjar (Ahmad Sanjar, 1086–1157, Seljuq sultan).[^4]\n\n**Other notes:**\n- **\"Sarguzasht-e-Adam\"** (Bang-E-Dara Part 1, Chapter 37) narrates humanity's journey allusively through figures like Adam (in the title), but evokes biblical/Quranic prophets (e.g., via Sinai for Moses, Hira Cave for Muhammad, the Cross for Jesus) without naming them directly.[^5]\n- Mythical or literary figures (e.g., Joseph/Zulaikha, Layla/Qais, Sa'di) appear symbolically but are not historical.[^1]\n- No other Iqbal poems in the corpus name specific historical figures by name. Searches for additional names (e.g., prophets, rulers) yielded no matches, and chapter reviews confirm this focus.\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, Chapter 8: \"Abdul Qadir Ke Naam\" (/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/08-abdul-qadir-ke-naam/translation/).\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, Chapter 23: \"Swami Ram Tirath\" (/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/23-swami-ram-tirath/translation/).\n[^3]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, Chapter 17: \"Ram\" (/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/17-ram/translation/).\n[^4]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, Chapter 24: \"Tazmeen bar sher-e Aneesi Shamlu\" (/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/24-tazmeen-bar-sher-e-aneesi-shamlu/translation/).\n[^5]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, Chapter 37: \"Sarguzasht-e-Adam\" (/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/37-sarguzasht-e-adam/translation/).",
